      <p>
        I'm a system architect at Houston Methodist with 10 years of experience
        in medical imaging and clinical data infrastructure. My career has traced
        a path from electrical engineering through DICOM imaging pipelines, HPC
        environments, and research platform architecture — always at the intersection
        of healthcare and technology.
      </p>
      <p>
        I've built PHI de-identification pipelines, containerized ML models for
        cross-institutional deployment, and scaled platforms like REDCap and XNAT
        from departmental tools to enterprise-wide systems. I collaborate closely
        with Rice University on research data engineering for clinical imaging studies.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now I'm pivoting into AI orchestration — building agentic systems that use
        LLMs to automate clinical workflows while respecting the constraints that
        make healthcare hard: PHI compliance, regulatory requirements, and the need
        for human-verifiable outputs. My graduate work at Georgia Tech in NLP,
        computer vision, and health informatics gives me the foundation; my years
        in the hospital give me the context that generic AI engineers can't fake.
      </p>
